# 📄 FIR & Court Document Analyzer - Week 04 Task

## 🎯 Project Overview
This project is an **AI-powered FIR & Court Document Analyzer** that uses a locally hosted Large Language Model (via **Ollama**) to read, summarize, and answer questions about First Information Reports (FIRs) and other court documents. It was built as part of the Week-04 internship task: *"Build Your Own AI Document Analyzer."*

The tool is designed to assist in quickly understanding legal and police documents by extracting key details — such as the date, time, location, and parties involved — and allowing users to ask natural-language questions to get instant, context-aware answers.

## 🛠️ Technologies Used
- **Python 3.10** – Core programming language
- **Ollama** – For running the LLM (`llama3.2`) locally, with no internet or paid API required
- **Streamlit** – To create an interactive web interface
- **Libraries:**
  - `pdfplumber` – for extracting text from PDF documents
  - `requests` – for communicating with the local Ollama API

## ✨ Key Features
- **Document Upload:** Upload an FIR or court document in `.pdf` or `.txt` format
- **Automatic Text Extraction:** Extracts readable text from the uploaded document, page by page
- **AI-Powered Summarization:** Generates a plain-English summary of the document, including key details like date, time, location, and parties involved
- **Interactive Q&A:** Ask any follow-up question about the uploaded document (e.g. *"Who filed this FIR?"*, *"What section was applied?"*) and get an instant AI-generated answer
- **Fully Local & Private:** All AI processing happens on your own machine via Ollama — no data is sent to any external server

## 🚀 How to Run the Application

### Prerequisites
- Python 3.9 or higher installed
- [Ollama](https://ollama.com/download) installed and running on your system
- The `llama3.2` model pulled locally:
```
ollama pull llama3.2
```

### Installation & Setup
1. Clone the repository (if you haven't already)
2. Navigate to the project directory:
```
cd week-4-fir-analyzer-document
```
3. Create and activate a virtual environment:
```
python -m venv venv
venv\Scripts\activate      # Windows
source venv/bin/activate   # Mac/Linux
```
4. Install the required Python packages:
```
pip install streamlit pdfplumber requests
```

### Running the Application
```
streamlit run app.py
```
This will open the app in your browser at `http://localhost:8501`, where you can:
1. Upload an FIR/court document (PDF or TXT)
2. Click **"Summarize Document"** to get an AI-generated summary
3. Type a question in the **"Ask a Question About This Document"** box and click **"Get Answer"**

## 📁 Project Structure
```
week-4-fir-analyzer-document/
├── app.py              # Main Streamlit application
└── venv/               # Virtual environment (not included in repo)
```

## 💡 How It Works
1. **Upload:** The user uploads an FIR/court document through the Streamlit interface
2. **Extract Text:** `pdfplumber` extracts raw text from the PDF page by page (or reads plain text directly for `.txt` files)
3. **AI Summarization:** The extracted text is sent to the locally running Ollama model (`llama3.2`) via its local API, asking it to summarize the document in plain English
4. **Interactive Q&A:** Any question typed by the user, along with the document text, is sent to the same model, which generates a contextual answer
5. **Display Results:** Both the summary and Q&A answers are displayed directly in the Streamlit interface

